## How many people cross the southern border each year?

The most detailed source of information about southern border crossings comes from  the Bureau of Transportation Statistics[bureau-transportation-statistics]

They've even got a nifty resource for querying the data yourself! Setting the query filters to only look for passengers and pedestrians over the U.S.-Mexico border shows
about 180M crossings per year[us-mexico-passengers]. However, this almost certainly doesn't include the vehicle drivers; the term 'occupant' is usually used
when including drivers, and BTS doesn't include 'Passengers' for Truck data (which  makes sense, assuming that trucks typically have no passengers).
Adding in the drivers (by allowing filters to count each truck, car, and bus) brings that number up to around 260 million 
[us-mexico-total-people].

 ## How many people enter the United States each year?

The BTS publishes data on inbound international flights that shows roughly 120M incoming airplane passengers each year (from international flights)[bts-inbound-international].

Using the same BTS query table from before (but widening our filters to include the U.S.-Canada border) shows over 320M total land-entries into the U.s. in a typical year.

Adding these numbers together gives us about 440 million total people who enter the United States in a typical year.  Of course,
the vast majority of these are either U.S. citizens (returning from trips abroad), or they are temporary foreign visitors (tourists, businessmen, etc).


 If a U.S. citizen family of five goes on two trips to Vancouver, that's ten separate occurrences of someone entering the United States.


